scripts.full_script: Worried about AI taking your job? You are not alone. But instead of panicking, ask yourself these three questions. First, does your job involve repetitive tasks? These are areas where humans still shine. If your job scores high on automation and low on creativity, it might be time to upskill. I am not saying you will lose your job but it is important to learn AI. Comment 'AI' and I will send you a list of free AI courses so you can stay ahead of the curve.

reels.spokenHook: You can now run a 70 billion parameter AI model with a graphics card that has just 4 gigs of RAM. This is Air LLM, a tool that lets you run huge AI models on small systems by loading only tiny parts of the model into memory at a time. So running a 70
reels.transcript: You can now run a 70 billion parameter AI model with a graphics card that has just 4 gigs of RAM. This is Air LLM, a tool that lets you run huge AI models on small systems by loading only tiny parts of the model into memory at a time. So running a 70 billion parameter model like Lama 3 normally requires 140 gigs of GPU memory. That's two enterprise GPUs that cost more than a car. But Air LLM does something clever. Instead of loading the entire model at once, it loads one layer at a time, runs the computation, and then frees the memory before loading the next layer. Think of it like reading a book one page at a time instead of holding the whole library in your hands. But there's a trade-off, it's slow and takes 4 to 35 seconds per response. So this isn't for real-time chatbots. And for researchers running experiments overnight, students learning AI without cloud bills, or startups processing thousands of documents in batches, this might be effective. As open source models keep getting better, the real challenge shifts from building smarter models to making them easier to run. And tools like AirLLM make adoption bigger, cheaper and actually practical.

reels.transcript: AI can now put MrBean inside Tom and Jerry cartoons and it looks completely real. So researchers just built an AI called MyMix that can take characters from completely different universes and make them interact naturally in the same video. Normally, AI video tools struggle when you try to mix cartoon characters with real people because they've never existed together in any training data. My mix solved this by teaching the AI to understand characters as separate concepts, like their appearance, how they move, and their personality quirks. All stored independently. So when you ask it to generate, We Bear Bears cooking with Tom and Jerry in a cartoon kitchen, it knows exactly how each one of them would stumble around and how Jerry would outsmart them. The researchers trained it on 81 hours of content, covering everything from Tom and Jerry to young Sheldon. And the AI preserves each character's original art style perfectly. Mr. Bean stays realistic while Tom stays animated, even when they're in the same frame. This is basically the beginning of AI that can create any crossover content you can imagine.
